Input: Head of the linked list.
Output: Head of the sorted linked list.

if (head == null || head.next == null)
Checks two base cases:
head == null → Empty list.
head.next == null → Only one node.
Such lists are already sorted.

return head; 
Return the list as it is.

ListNode slow = head;
Creates a slow pointer starting from the first node.

ListNode fast = head.next;
Creates a fast pointer starting from the second node.
Using head.next helps split the list evenly and avoids infinite recursion.

while (fast != null && fast.next != null)
Continue moving until fast reaches the end.
Need both conditions because fast moves two steps.

slow = slow.next;
Move slow pointer one step.

fast = fast.next.next;
Move fast pointer two steps.

Now slow is at the middle.

ListNode mid = slow.next;
Store the first node of the second half.

Complexity
Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(log n) (recursive call stack) 

